  Would a 20ft jon boat be better?  I like the idea of drifting the Little Red, but in reality don't know how much of a pain it would be if I'm always on the look out for spinner fishermen w/ anchored jon boats and the docks that line the river.  Any thoughts? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F9FBFD><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bflyfishingarkansasandmissouri.showUserPublicProfile?gid=andrewcolley@flyfishingarkansasandmissouri>Andrew Colley</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Little Red River Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#000000>(1/27/03 4:44 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm14.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=9.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Pontoon boats</span><hr size=1> Hey Softhackle,<br>
I have I have been fishing the Little Red for as long as I can remember, and have been guiding it, and other rivers in Arkansas, for almost 5 years.  Six years ago I had the same question you did and I elected to build a drift boat.  I still use it and guide out of it and personally consider drifting to be the most pleasurable way to fish the Little Red.  The only &quot;problem&quot; is found when you hit the long pooled areas.  This will make you want to have some sort of motor on whatever you decide upon.   A jon boat is fine, but for me it really limits what areas are accessable, but if you are not afraid to beat an aluminum boat up, then it is a good idea.  One jon boat pet peeve of many folks on the river are the jackrabbits that run their boats up the shoal at full bore.  It can really play hell on a shoal.<br>
About 2 years ago I looked into getting a Cataraft to guide on our wonderful tailwaters.  They are pretty nice, and the newer ones really tend to row well.  The only set back is the cost.  For the cataraft and rafts I looked into purchasing, I was looking at the same as a brand new Clackacraft!    I think you could easily set up a jon boat to fish the Little Red for a couple grand, but would recommend at least an 80-100 guage botton, and an epoxy/graphite coat on the bottom to reduce drag and help loose the aluminum grabbing characteristics.  Also look into a 4-stroke, as they are very VERY river friendly<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
~Andrew <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> softhackle</span><br> <span class=usertitle>Unregistered User</span><br>   <font color=#000000>(1/27/03 8:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm14.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=9.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> pontoon boats</span><hr size=1> andrew, thanks for the input.  I've been eyeing the 2 person pontoon boat in cabelas for $999.  Probably couldn't handle a motor, but doesn't cost much.  Probably not very durable though.  It's tempting.  I'll let you know what I decide.  Thanks again. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F9FBFD><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bflyfishingarkansasandmissouri.showUserPublicProfile?gid=flyfishar>FlyFishAR</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 39<br> <font color=#000000>(1/27/03 8:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm14.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=9.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://boards.justflies.com/Images/4/4551Photo1.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: pontoon boats</span><hr size=1> Andrew:<br>
<br>
Why is it that 98% of the boats on the White are fiberglass and half of them on the Lil Red are aluminum? I can understand the difference in prop vs. jet, but I would have thought fiberglass would allow them to absord contact with rocks better. <br>
<br>
John <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bflyfishingarkansasandmissouri.showUserPublicProfile?gid=andrewcolley@flyfishingarkansasandmissouri>Andrew Colley</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Little Red River Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 8<br> <font color=#000000>(1/28/03 12:28 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm14.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=9.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: pontoon boats</span><hr size=1> Softhackle,<br>
That is a pretty cool boat, and I bet it would give you a lifetime of faithful service.  That is exactly what you need to float from CowShoals to Swinging Bridge.  That's where the big boys, and girls, play at a frightening frequency.   I used to make that float with really good fishermen from time to time, but it always took a while to get a drift doat down the bank.  But seriously, there are about 6 &quot;spots&quot; to make constant drifts to all day on that float.  You could go nuts watching the HUGE bows, much less the big browns in that stretch.  <br>
<br>
John, I think the reason there are so many aluminum boats on the Red, is that it is not the &quot;destination&quot; river that the White is reputed to be.  An interesting study would be to ask folks what is the primary use for their boat.  I bet on the White it would be trout, and the Red would probably typical jon boat usage(duck, general fishing, etc.) and trout.   <br>
Although the usage of the typical &quot;White River Boat&quot; is unquestionable, I am a firm believer that ANY river boat with a &quot;Gel Coat,&quot; is poorly designed.  There is probably no worse outer coating a boat manufacturer could put on a boat that is going to take abuse.  But, if you are going to hit a rock, you are going to hit a rock.  I just dont like the marks.  It just looks....well, you know.<br>
~Andrew <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm14.showPrevMessage?topicID=9.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm14.showNextMessage?topicID=9.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a self href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm14.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=9.topic&index=4><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/addReply1.gif border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"> <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm14.emailToFriend?topicID=9.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/email.gif border=0 alt="Email This To a Friend"> Email This To a Friend</a><br> <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm14.threadControl?topicID=9.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/deleteThreadFire.gif border=0 alt="Topic Control Image"> Topic Commands</a><br> <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm14.subscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=9.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/ultimate/subscribe.gif width=20 height=20 border=0 alt="Click to receive email notification of replies"> Click to receive email notification of replies</a> <br>  <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm14.unsubscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=9.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/ultimate/unsubscribe.gif width=20 height=20 border=0 alt="Click to stop receiving email notification of replies"> Click to stop receiving email notification of replies</a> <br> </td><td align="right" valign="top"></td></tr><tr align="right"><td colspan=2><form action=http://pub98.ezboard.com/BBSForum.jumpShowForum method=post><table border="0" cellspacing="0" 